Performance Analysis and Vehicle Characteristics in the “Dakar Desert Rally”

Leandro Fermino Uchôa

October / 2024

Introduction

Hello, my name is Leandro Fermino Uchôa, and this document is part of my capstone project for the Google Data Analytics Professional Certificate, offered by Google through the Coursera platform (course link). The goal of this project is to analyze the performance and characteristics of vehicles in the game “Dakar Desert Rally” (official site), using detailed data to identify which vehicles perform best and how these characteristics influence price and player choice.

About the Game

“Dakar Desert Rally” is a racing game that simulates the famous Dakar rally, offering a realistic and challenging experience for players. The version of the game used for this analysis includes the base game and the DLC “Dakar Desert Rally - SnowRunner Cars Pack”.

Project Objective

The objective of this project is to: - Identify which vehicles perform best in terms of speed, durability, and other characteristics. - Analyze how these characteristics influence price and player choice. - Provide insights that can help improve vehicle balancing in the game, inform decisions about updates and new releases, and develop more effective marketing strategies.

Delivery: Clear statement of the business task and the insights obtained. 4. References: Sources of data and information used in the project.

Phase 2: Data Preparation

1. Where is your data located?

The data is located in a CSV file that was imported into RStudio. The file was originally checked and cleaned in Excel before being exported to RStudio.

2. How is the data organized?

The data is organized in a wide format, where each row represents a vehicle and each column represents a specific attribute of that vehicle.

3. Are there any issues with bias or credibility in this data? Is your data reliable, original, comprehensive, current, and does it include the source?

The data comes from the game “Dakar Desert Rally” released on 4/Oct/2022. So it is still comprehensive and current, especially considering the game universe itself. As for completeness and completeness, both have already been reviewed to ensure there is no bias.

4. How are you handling licensing, privacy, security, and accessibility?

The data is from a game, so we are adhering to the game’s terms of use and licensing. There is no sensitive personal data, so privacy and security are less of a concern here.

5. How did you verify data integrity?

Data integrity was ensured through a thorough check in Excel. In this process, I eliminated missing and duplicate values, removed unnecessary whitespace at the beginning and end of cells, and standardized column names for consistency. It is important to note that the ‘Price_DP’ field intentionally contains ‘NA’ values, aiming for more efficient analysis of the dataset. Here is the code used to check the integrity of the data in the R environment:

Phase 3: Process the Data

I am using Excel for initial data cleaning and R with the dplyr and tidyr packages for data manipulation and verification. Excel is an intuitive and effective tool for data cleaning, while R is powerful for data manipulation and integrity checking.

2. Have you ensured the integrity of your data?

Yes, data integrity was ensured through detailed checks in Excel, where I removed missing and duplicate values, and standardized column names. I then confirmed the integrity of the data in R.

3. What steps were taken to ensure that your data is clean?

In Excel, I removed missing and duplicate values, eliminated unnecessary whitespace, and standardized column names. In R, I used functions to check for missing and duplicate values, and to ensure data consistency.

4. How can you check if your data is clean and ready for analysis?

By checking for missing and duplicate values ​​in R, and using summary functions to ensure that the data is consistent and ready for analysis.

5. Did you document your cleaning process so that you can review and share the results?

Yes, the entire cleaning process was documented in Excel and committed to RMarkdown code, allowing you to review and share the results.

1. Descriptive Summary of Key Measures of a Data Set:

In this descriptive summary, I present the key measures of a data set, including minimum, first quartile, median, mean, third quartile, and maximum:

  • Min. (Minimum): The smallest value in the data set.
  • 1st Qu. (First Quartile): The value below which 25% of the data lies.
  • Median (Median): The central value that divides the data set into two equal halves.
  • Mean (Mean): The arithmetic mean of the values.
  • 3rd Qu. (Third Quartile): The value below which 75% of the data lies.
  • Max. (Maximum): The largest value in the data set.

These values help to understand the distribution of the data, showing the central tendency and dispersion.

3. Vehicle Type Proportion Analysis:

In this analysis, we present a visual representation that illustrates the proportion of different vehicle types (Vehicle_Type) in the game as a whole. Each “slice” of the graph represents a vehicle type (Vehicle_Type), and its size is proportional to the percentage of that category in relation to the total.

# Create the total_vehicles_type dataframe from the DDR_Vehicles_List_Stats_df
total_veiculos_tipo <- DDR_Vehicles_List_Stats_df %>%
  group_by(Vehicle_Type) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  mutate(percentage = (n / sum(n)) * 100)

# Pie chart showing the contribution of vehicle types to the total
ggplot(total_veiculos_tipo, aes(x = "", y = n, fill = Vehicle_Type)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity", color = "black") +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(percentage, 1), "%")), 
            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 4) +
  ggtitle("Proportion of Vehicle Types") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14, face = "bold"),
    axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.grid = element_blank(),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 10)
  )

4. Histogram Analysis of Price Distribution by Vehicle Type:

This histogram shows the price distribution (DP) by vehicle type (Vehicle_Type). The bars represent the frequency of vehicles in different price ranges, with distinct colors for each vehicle type. The bar width is set to 500 price units, and the chart uses the “Set1” color palette to differentiate vehicle types.

# Filter records with N/A values in Price_DP
filtered_data <- DDR_Vehicles_List_Stats_df[!is.na(DDR_Vehicles_List_Stats_df$Price_DP), ]

# Histogram of Price Distribution by Vehicle Type
ggplot(data = filtered_data, aes(x = Price_DP, fill = Vehicle_Type)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 500, color = "black", alpha = 0.7, position = "dodge") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  ggtitle("Price Distribution (DP) by Vehicle Type") +
  xlab("Price (DP)") +
  ylab("Frequency") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14, face = "bold"),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 10)
  )

5. Scatterplot Analysis of the Relationship between Price and Team Score by Vehicle Type:

This scatterplot illustrates the relationship between the price (DP) and the Team Score of the vehicles in the database. Each point on the graph represents a vehicle, with the shape and color indicating the vehicle type. Through this graph, we can observe how different types of vehicles are distributed in terms of price and performance, allowing a visual analysis of the trends and patterns present in the data.

# Filter records with N/A values in Price_DP
filtered_data <- DDR_Vehicles_List_Stats_df[!is.na(DDR_Vehicles_List_Stats_df$Price_DP), ]

# Code common to all graphs in the sequence
# Define the shapes for each type of vehicle
shapes <- c("Cars" = 16, "Trucks" = 15, "Bikes" = 17, "Quads" = 18, "SxS" = 19)  # 16: ball, 15: square, 17: triangle, 18: rhombus, 19: filled circle

# Scatterplot for Price vs. Team Score
ggplot(data = filtered_data, aes(x = Price_DP, y = Team_Score, shape = Vehicle_Type, color = Vehicle_Type)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = shapes) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  ggtitle("Price (DP) vs. Team Score") +
  xlab("Price (DP)") +
  ylab("Team Score") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14, face = "bold"),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.position = "none"
  )+
  facet_wrap(~ Vehicle_Type, scales = "free")

6. Correlation Analysis of Vehicle Attributes:

The graph below shows the correlation matrix for vehicle attributes, generated from the numeric columns of the DDR_Vehicles_List_Stats_df dataset. Using the ggcorrplot function, the colored circles indicate the strength and direction of the correlations: blue for positive correlations and red for negative correlations. The intensity of the color and the size of the circles reflect the magnitude of the correlation.

This graph helps identify meaningful relationships between vehicle attributes, aiding in informed analysis and decision-making.

# Code Explanation
# select(...): Selects only the numeric columns relevant to the correlation.
# cor(numerical_columns, use = "complete.obs"): Calculates the correlation matrix, ignoring missing values.
# ggcorrplot(...): Plots the correlation matrix with colored circles, where the size and color of the circles indicate the strength and direction of the correlation.
# Interpretation
# Colors: Blue indicates positive correlation, red indicates negative correlation, and white indicates little or no correlation.
# Circle Size: Larger circles indicate stronger correlations.

# Select only numeric columns for correlation
numerical_columns <- DDR_Vehicles_List_Stats_df %>%
  select(Team_Score, Speed, Acceleration, Handling, Durability, Power_hp, Torque_Nm, Top_Speed_km_h, Price_DP, Full_Stats_No_TS, Full_Stats_With_TS)

# Calculate the correlation matrix
cor_matrix <- cor(numerical_columns, use = "complete.obs")

# Plot the correlation matrix
ggcorrplot(cor_matrix, 
           method = "circle", 
           type = "lower", 
           lab = TRUE, 
           lab_size = 3, 
           colors = c("red", "white", "blue"), 
           title = "Vehicle Attribute Correlation Matrix", 
           ggtheme = theme_minimal())

7. Price Distribution by Vehicle Type:

The graph below shows a boxplot comparing the distribution of prices (SD) by vehicle type in the DDR_Vehicles_List_Stats_df dataset. Using the ggplot2 function, each boxplot represents the variation in prices within each vehicle category, highlighting the median, quartiles, and possible outliers. The colors were applied using the “Set1” palette for easy visualization.

This graph is useful for identifying differences and patterns in the prices of different vehicle types.

  )

The graph below shows the distribution of vehicle types by driver nationality in the DDR_Vehicles_List_Stats_df dataset. Conclusion:

Once the visualizations have been created and several insights have been generated from them, it is time to conclude the study.

The insights gained from this analysis can help players and developers better understand the characteristics and performance of vehicles in the “Dakar Desert Rally” game. Another interesting point observed, frequently mentioned by the gaming community, is the importance of the “Team Score”. When analyzing this parameter, it initially does not seem to have a significant impact on the car’s performance. However, I believe that a new study focused on this premise is necessary to confirm this observation.
